WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:35.035 --> 00:35.969
Amelia, thank you for agreeing

00:35.970 --> 00:37.270
to do this interview.

00:37.271 --> 00:38.771
Thank you for coming.

00:38.772 --> 00:40.273
Thank you.

00:40.274 --> 00:43.343
I'm a little nervous.

00:43.344 --> 00:45.678
Really? How so?

00:45.679 --> 00:48.181
Cameras, people watching,

00:48.182 --> 00:51.784
kind of feeling the
pressure, you know?

00:51.785 --> 00:54.254
What I actually
mean is some people

00:54.255 --> 00:56.623
may be asking how
it's possible for you

00:56.624 --> 01:00.761
to even feel nervousness
considering what you are.

01:01.929 --> 01:03.396
How did you feel
when you realized

01:03.397 --> 01:05.899
that you were no longer human?

01:18.212 --> 01:19.446
What we're working on

01:19.447 --> 01:21.981
is going to change the world.

01:21.982 --> 01:23.650
Scientists have known for years

01:23.651 --> 01:26.453
that the human brain is
essentially an electrical device.

01:26.454 --> 01:29.456
Beginning data stream in 10...

01:32.426 --> 01:34.060
Seven, six.

01:34.061 --> 01:36.396
That's where our memories
are, everything about us.

01:36.397 --> 01:38.466
Our hopes, fears, dreams.

01:43.204 --> 01:45.639
Six, five, four.

01:46.940 --> 01:49.176
Transmitting neural
impulses from the brain

01:49.177 --> 01:50.310
is nothing new.

01:50.311 --> 01:52.245
This, this is the next step.

01:52.246 --> 01:54.347
Containing those connections.

01:54.348 --> 01:57.984
We can't return life
that's already lost.

02:00.388 --> 02:02.189
But, we might be
able to intercede

02:02.190 --> 02:04.257
before the moment of death

02:04.258 --> 02:06.125
and rescue a person's
consciousness

02:06.126 --> 02:08.461
before it's lost forever.

02:13.401 --> 02:15.101
If we can do that,
then that is the key

02:15.102 --> 02:18.672
to living forever, to
saving those we love.

02:24.478 --> 02:27.648
To saving those who
leave us too soon.

02:30.117 --> 02:32.985
That's what we're trying to do.

02:32.986 --> 02:35.288
Every day we learn new ways

02:35.289 --> 02:37.657
to conquer the limits
of the human body.

02:37.658 --> 02:41.961
We're approaching new
worlds, new frontiers,

02:41.962 --> 02:43.730
and new possibilities for life.

02:43.731 --> 02:46.833
And I will tell you, we
are already looking forward

02:46.834 --> 02:49.001
to the students,
to the pioneers,

02:49.002 --> 02:50.470
and the breakthroughs
yet to come.

02:50.471 --> 02:53.406
Each day we hear new
ideas, see new projects,

02:53.407 --> 02:55.107
and we meet new heroes.

02:55.108 --> 02:57.244
Here's to building
a better future.

02:57.245 --> 02:59.279
Here's to building
better people.

03:24.272 --> 03:28.442
Dad used to say that life
was like a light switch.

03:30.478 --> 03:33.381
You die and you're
just turned off.

03:37.017 --> 03:39.787
I don't think he
was ever afraid.

03:44.191 --> 03:45.859
What do you think?

03:52.666 --> 03:55.403
Still not used to it, you know?

04:06.780 --> 04:07.780
Just...

04:08.949 --> 04:11.519
Tell me what you need me to do.

04:16.457 --> 04:19.059
Stay safe out there.

04:20.260 --> 04:21.894
Here's the thing, Adah,

04:21.894 --> 04:24.431
there's no such thing as
the natural order of life.

04:24.432 --> 04:26.733
You're saying in your
book that transhumanism

04:26.734 --> 04:30.036
is humanity escaping the
bounds of the human body,

04:30.037 --> 04:32.372
but again, keep in mind
we're talking to everyone

04:32.373 --> 04:35.408
that has the main
idea that humanity

04:35.409 --> 04:39.579
is having flesh and
bones, being human itself

04:39.580 --> 04:40.980
and having a physical body.

04:40.981 --> 04:42.081
Everything that we engineer,

04:42.082 --> 04:43.583
everything that we do...

04:43.584 --> 04:45.919
For lunch there is celery.

04:47.020 --> 04:48.355
You need to tell
that partner of yours

04:48.356 --> 04:50.457
that he's a bad
influence on you.

04:50.458 --> 04:52.759
Gotta keep you
lookin' good, mister.

04:52.760 --> 04:54.026
Mm-hm.

04:54.027 --> 04:57.498
Maybe I can just call
in sick to work and...

05:00.334 --> 05:02.168
You know, one of these
days I got to tell Amelia

05:02.169 --> 05:04.637
I need more calories
than a ham sandwich.

05:04.638 --> 05:06.138
Enjoy it while it lasts.

05:06.139 --> 05:09.576
Still have things about
each other you don't know.

05:09.577 --> 05:11.110
That's not true, Vaughan.

05:11.111 --> 05:13.613
Carter, I've been
married since college.

05:13.614 --> 05:15.247
You got five months tops, right,

05:15.248 --> 05:17.550
and then she accidentally
leaves the bathroom door open

05:17.551 --> 05:20.019
or forgets to flush.

05:20.020 --> 05:22.589
Next thing you know,
seven years go by

05:22.590 --> 05:24.323
and you got a mortgage.

05:24.324 --> 05:25.558
She starts talkin' about kids.

05:25.559 --> 05:27.794
You guys have talked
about that, right?

05:27.795 --> 05:28.795
Yeah.

05:31.565 --> 05:33.333
I mean, not recently.

05:38.238 --> 05:40.373
What the hell's so funny.

05:40.374 --> 05:41.841
Oh, it's comin'.

05:41.842 --> 05:45.211
Oh, welcome to the club
of former honeymooners.

05:45.212 --> 05:47.980
You better start
picking out baby names.

05:47.981 --> 05:48.982
Until then,

05:51.051 --> 05:52.386
enjoy this time.

05:53.387 --> 05:54.621
I am.

05:54.622 --> 05:55.556
And you know what, I'm
actually looking forward

05:55.557 --> 05:56.889
to picking out baby names.

05:57.925 --> 05:59.191
I am.

05:59.192 --> 06:00.593
All units be advised,

06:00.594 --> 06:02.028
reports of a mentally unstable
man on Lily Boulevard.

06:02.029 --> 06:03.696
Can I get a responder?

06:03.697 --> 06:05.264
So much for lunch.

06:19.179 --> 06:21.849
Are you okay, Mrs. Summerland?

06:26.119 --> 06:27.520
Did you forget something?

06:27.521 --> 06:28.888
Yeah, my tablet.

06:28.889 --> 06:30.824
Yeah, right.

06:45.839 --> 06:46.839
Sir?

06:55.215 --> 06:56.783
Sir, I need
you to take your hands

06:56.784 --> 06:58.452
out of your pockets.

07:00.287 --> 07:04.224
It's a beautiful
day, don't ya think?

07:09.463 --> 07:11.532
Look, take it easy, okay?

07:34.922 --> 07:37.356
Why didn't you shoot me?

07:37.357 --> 07:38.291
It's all right.

07:38.292 --> 07:40.360
It's all right, it's over.

07:41.629 --> 07:42.895
You all right?

07:42.896 --> 07:43.963
I'm gonna need you
to put your hands

07:43.964 --> 07:46.299
behind your back, all right?

08:00.413 --> 08:01.413
Amelia!

08:32.645 --> 08:34.714
Carter.

08:51.331 --> 08:53.032
So, Andrew's leaning
up against the bar,

08:53.033 --> 08:55.534
now bear in mind he's really
drunk right now, right?

08:55.535 --> 08:57.670
And this woman, she
saddles up next to him

08:57.671 --> 09:00.072
and she says, "When
a woman asks you"

09:00.073 --> 09:02.909
"how old you think she
is, take your best guess"

09:02.910 --> 09:05.411
"and subtract by 10."

09:05.412 --> 09:08.615
And Andrew here
just goes, "I did."

09:13.420 --> 09:17.389
Hey, Carter, we're heading
to the Starlight tonight

09:17.390 --> 09:19.225
if you wanna come.

09:19.226 --> 09:20.661
Yeah, I'll see.

09:21.962 --> 09:24.698
Tell her hey for me, all right?

09:51.358 --> 09:52.693
Hey beautiful.

09:59.499 --> 10:01.168
Brought you flowers.

10:18.051 --> 10:19.152
I missed you.

10:23.490 --> 10:25.491
Got big news today.

10:25.492 --> 10:28.160
It has been exactly
six months this week

10:28.161 --> 10:30.730
since I stopped energy drinks

10:30.731 --> 10:34.033
and I've been taking
lunch to work.

10:34.034 --> 10:35.034
Mostly.

11:30.958 --> 11:32.124
I thought it was good!

11:32.125 --> 11:33.325
- Really?
- I liked it.

11:33.326 --> 11:34.660
You couldn't have,
you fell asleep.

11:34.661 --> 11:35.661
It was, I...

11:36.764 --> 11:37.797
But before that,
before I fell asleep,

11:37.798 --> 11:38.965
I thought it was fun.

11:38.966 --> 11:41.400
For three minutes?

11:41.401 --> 11:42.903
Uh-huh.

11:44.805 --> 11:47.006
So, what else do you wanna do?

11:47.007 --> 11:48.674
When you're not
ticketing adorable women

11:48.675 --> 11:50.609
for going five over.

11:50.610 --> 11:52.244
Adorable, huh?

11:52.245 --> 11:53.545
And smart.

11:53.546 --> 11:55.181
Okay.

11:55.182 --> 11:56.182
And funny.

11:56.183 --> 11:57.017
- Uh-huh.
- Yeah?

11:57.018 --> 11:58.117
Uh-huh.

11:58.118 --> 12:00.186
What do you do?

12:00.187 --> 12:01.388
I don't know.

12:03.156 --> 12:04.657
Really? Come on.

12:05.558 --> 12:07.795
There's got to be somethin'.

12:12.833 --> 12:16.302
Maybe a little
street piano playing?

12:17.971 --> 12:19.738
No, I could

12:19.739 --> 12:23.109
never really push a
piano down the street.

12:23.110 --> 12:24.210
Ha!

12:24.211 --> 12:25.845
They are heavy.

12:25.846 --> 12:27.546
Just sayin'.

12:27.547 --> 12:29.615
All right, okay.

12:29.616 --> 12:33.787
So you're not very strong,
I got that.

12:35.622 --> 12:38.925
How about something you can
do or that you like to do.

12:38.926 --> 12:39.926
Anything.

12:40.928 --> 12:41.928
Something.

12:44.197 --> 12:46.198
How 'bout I show you?

12:46.199 --> 12:47.199
Okay.

12:50.070 --> 12:51.071
What's that?

13:29.209 --> 13:30.209
Jesus.

13:34.982 --> 13:36.782
Thanks for answering your phone.

13:36.783 --> 13:40.252
I thought you had plans
tonight with the guys.

13:40.253 --> 13:41.253
Yeah.

13:44.157 --> 13:45.624
How are you?

13:45.625 --> 13:46.893
I'm great.

13:46.894 --> 13:48.294
I paid off another installment.

13:48.295 --> 13:49.528
I applied for the Wesley grant.

13:49.529 --> 13:51.263
I'm using my site
to raise donations.

13:51.264 --> 13:52.764
Oh.

13:52.765 --> 13:55.701
Thought you said you were two
months behind on your house.

13:55.702 --> 13:56.702
Yeah.

13:58.838 --> 14:01.974
Amelia's got maybe a
few more months, maybe.

14:01.975 --> 14:03.911
But there's still time.

14:07.480 --> 14:08.748
Look, Carter.

14:10.850 --> 14:14.021
I know it's tough
to let go, I get it.

14:17.925 --> 14:21.627
If there's anything
you need, let me know.

14:21.628 --> 14:23.196
I need more time.

14:26.033 --> 14:28.901
Every day we learn new
ways to conquer the limits

14:28.902 --> 14:30.970
of the human body.

14:30.971 --> 14:34.573
We're approaching new
worlds, new frontiers,

14:34.574 --> 14:37.343
and new possibilities for life.

14:37.344 --> 14:39.979
So, while I thank you for
this award I will tell you,

14:39.980 --> 14:42.014
we are already looking forward

14:42.015 --> 14:44.016
to the students,
to the pioneers,

14:44.017 --> 14:45.351
to the breakthroughs
yet to come.

14:45.352 --> 14:48.187
Each day we hear new
ideas, see new projects,

14:48.188 --> 14:49.888
and we meet new heroes.

14:49.889 --> 14:51.890
Here's to building
a better future.

14:51.891 --> 14:54.193
Here's to building
better people.

15:00.900 --> 15:02.268
Of course I can't believe it.

15:02.269 --> 15:03.269
Paul Wesley.

15:03.270 --> 15:05.037
Well, congrats.

15:05.038 --> 15:06.272
Well, thank you.

15:06.273 --> 15:07.473
So, Paul Wesley, when
are you gonna start

15:07.474 --> 15:08.941
returning my phone calls?

15:08.942 --> 15:11.343
When your show stops pandering
to corn fed housewives.

15:11.344 --> 15:13.946
Tell you producers to reach
outside the box they're in.

15:13.947 --> 15:15.214
- Ooh, ouch.
- Ow.

15:15.215 --> 15:16.282
I was referring to
dinner, but I think

15:16.283 --> 15:17.849
I'll rescind the offer.

15:17.850 --> 15:19.351
Good to see ya, Adah.

15:19.352 --> 15:20.187
Take this.

15:20.188 --> 15:21.420
Yeah.

15:21.421 --> 15:22.754
I'm on a flight in
30 minutes, Ellen.

15:22.755 --> 15:23.990
What have you got?

15:23.991 --> 15:27.159
I think we have a candidate.

15:27.160 --> 15:28.660
The leukemia patient?

15:28.661 --> 15:30.629
No, he's made a full recovery.

15:30.630 --> 15:32.331
That's unfortunate.

15:32.332 --> 15:36.202
Amelia Summerland,
age 26, coma patient.

15:36.203 --> 15:37.436
Aneurysm two years ago.

15:37.437 --> 15:39.271
Diagnosis of Locked-in syndrome.

15:39.272 --> 15:41.807
The brain is fully intact
but much left on her body.

15:41.808 --> 15:42.975
She's married?

15:42.976 --> 15:44.410
Yes, Carter Summerland.

15:44.411 --> 15:45.345
I'm sorry, do I know you?

15:45.346 --> 15:46.612
I'm Paul Wesley.

15:46.613 --> 15:48.347
I believe you applied
for one of my grants.

15:48.348 --> 15:50.916
We need to speak to you
immediately about Amelia.

15:50.917 --> 15:52.818
Any other family
members our lawyers

15:52.819 --> 15:53.919
have to worry about?

15:53.920 --> 15:54.854
She's an only child.

15:54.854 --> 15:55.788
Her parents are deceased.

15:55.789 --> 15:57.156
Mr. Summerland, do you know

15:57.157 --> 15:59.291
what a non-disclosure
agreement is?

15:59.292 --> 16:00.093
Yeah.

16:00.094 --> 16:01.127
Good.

16:01.128 --> 16:02.128
Sign that.

16:55.182 --> 16:57.116
Max, just in time.

16:57.117 --> 16:58.784
Mr. Summerland,
nice to meet you.

16:58.785 --> 17:00.419
Max Parker, lead robotics.

17:00.420 --> 17:02.020
We're excited to
show you the lab.

17:02.021 --> 17:03.522
Right this way.

17:03.523 --> 17:06.525
Now entering
cyber level four, section D.

17:06.526 --> 17:09.994
All right, all non-essential
personnel, clear out.

17:09.996 --> 17:13.632
Carter, I want you to
meet Dr. Ellen Beckett.

17:13.633 --> 17:15.334
Very nice to meet
you, Mr. Summerland.

17:15.335 --> 17:16.602
Dr. Beckett is the
chief neurologist

17:16.603 --> 17:18.304
for Wesley Enterprises.

17:18.305 --> 17:20.205
She's been studying
Amelia's scans.

17:20.207 --> 17:22.040
Most coma patients have seen

17:22.040 --> 17:24.710
significant deterioration
by this point.

17:24.711 --> 17:26.578
I think there's a
wonderful chance

17:26.579 --> 17:29.248
that your wife is
still in there.

17:29.249 --> 17:30.416
Dr. Beckett is the main reason

17:30.417 --> 17:31.483
we've made such progress
in brain injuries

17:31.484 --> 17:33.152
over the past 10 years.

17:33.153 --> 17:34.753
You can fix Amelia?

17:34.754 --> 17:36.222
Better.

17:36.223 --> 17:39.959
Mr. Summerland, I'd
like you to meet Cindy 69.

17:41.328 --> 17:43.329
Go ahead, touch her.

17:43.330 --> 17:44.830
This is the latest generation

17:44.831 --> 17:47.833
of the Cindy 69 companion robot.

17:47.834 --> 17:49.235
My design.

17:49.236 --> 17:50.669
Max, couldn't you
have brought down

17:50.670 --> 17:52.171
one of the elderly
assistance models?

17:52.172 --> 17:54.306
But Mr. Wesley,
this model has the latest

17:54.307 --> 17:56.242
biosynthetic flesh, state of...

17:56.243 --> 17:58.043
Online.

17:58.044 --> 17:59.345
That feels real nice.

17:59.346 --> 18:00.579
Sorry.

18:00.580 --> 18:01.281
That feels real nice.

18:01.282 --> 18:02.548
Okay, sorry.

18:02.549 --> 18:03.815
- That feels real...
- Sorry about that.

18:03.816 --> 18:06.886
I didn't think she
was activated yet.

18:08.054 --> 18:09.521
I don't understand.

18:09.522 --> 18:10.789
I apologize, Carter.

18:10.790 --> 18:12.691
Max's social skills
aside, you can tell

18:12.692 --> 18:16.462
that this technology is
indistinguishable from human flesh.

18:16.463 --> 18:19.665
Mr. Summerland,
we can help Amelia

18:19.666 --> 18:23.535
by putting her brain
into a new body.

18:23.536 --> 18:24.770
Into that?

18:24.771 --> 18:28.974
We can build an exact
replica of your wife.

18:33.146 --> 18:36.248
Wait, Mr. Summerland,
we can help you.

18:36.249 --> 18:37.483
You wanna help me?

18:37.484 --> 18:39.050
Put Amelia in a better facility.

18:39.051 --> 18:41.187
Find me someone who
understands Locked-in Syndrome.

18:41.188 --> 18:42.088
But that?

18:42.089 --> 18:43.389
It's not even human.

18:43.390 --> 18:47.058
We have artificial
hearts, artificial hips.

18:47.059 --> 18:48.760
We've been replacing
worn out parts

18:48.761 --> 18:51.363
on ourselves for the
better part of a century.

18:51.364 --> 18:52.931
You can't tell me
that's the same thing.

18:52.932 --> 18:56.335
Mr. Summerland, can
I put it another way?

18:56.336 --> 18:57.336
Kim.

18:58.605 --> 19:03.375
Okay, say I wanted to replace
the front end of this pen.

19:03.376 --> 19:06.546
I take it off, put
a new front end on.

19:08.481 --> 19:10.048
Ta-da, there's my pen.

19:10.049 --> 19:12.751
But wait, what if I want to
replace the other half of it?

19:12.752 --> 19:13.686
No problem.

19:13.687 --> 19:15.987
I just unscrew that, right?

19:15.988 --> 19:18.490
Screw a new backend on.

19:18.491 --> 19:20.058
There's my pen.

19:20.059 --> 19:24.162
Uh-oh, but look, here are the
two pieces that I replaced.

19:24.163 --> 19:28.066
If I were to put
these back together...

19:28.067 --> 19:30.436
Would that be the original pen?

19:30.437 --> 19:33.572
Or is that the original pen now?

19:33.573 --> 19:34.906
Hm?

19:34.907 --> 19:36.075
Do you get it?

19:42.949 --> 19:44.750
You've agreed to
complete secrecy.

19:44.751 --> 19:48.720
You discuss this with anyone,
the offer's off the table.

20:03.570 --> 20:05.871
I once had a daughter.

20:05.872 --> 20:08.740
In five seconds I went
from driving her to school

20:08.741 --> 20:11.077
to a bed just like this one.

20:13.880 --> 20:17.383
We chose Amelia
because she's young.

20:17.384 --> 20:20.752
Her mind is healthy and
we know when and how

20:20.753 --> 20:22.588
she's going to die.

20:22.589 --> 20:26.625
We're offering you
the chance to see her,

20:26.626 --> 20:28.127
to hold her again.

20:34.967 --> 20:36.502
If I say yes, what happens?

20:36.503 --> 20:38.169
You would sign power of attorney

20:38.170 --> 20:39.538
over to Wesley Enterprises.

20:39.539 --> 20:41.740
You would give consent
on your wife's behalf

20:41.741 --> 20:43.275
to this procedure.

20:43.276 --> 20:45.877
When your wife passes
away, they take her body.

20:45.878 --> 20:48.480
She gets officially donated
to scientific research,

20:48.481 --> 20:49.981
but we stay discreet.

20:49.982 --> 20:52.351
We then preserve her
brain and begin a process

20:52.352 --> 20:53.652
we call mapping.

20:53.653 --> 20:54.886
How long does that take?

20:54.887 --> 20:56.322
We need to acclimate
her to a new body

20:56.323 --> 20:58.590
and she'll require
therapy, physical, mental.

20:58.591 --> 21:00.560
It's gonna be some time.

22:15.001 --> 22:16.535
We ask that you
comfort us in this time

22:16.536 --> 22:18.003
and for the future.

22:18.004 --> 22:20.105
It is with our faith in you
that we commit her body,

22:20.106 --> 22:23.275
her heart, her being,
into your hands.

22:26.646 --> 22:29.114
Insiders suggest
something big on the horizon

22:29.115 --> 22:31.817
for the multi-billion
dollar research facility.

22:31.818 --> 22:33.885
Many may remember
Wesley Enterprises

22:33.886 --> 22:36.087
was in a similar situation
just a few years ago.

22:36.088 --> 22:38.023
What else do you wanna do?

22:38.024 --> 22:39.991
When you're not
ticketing adorable women

22:39.992 --> 22:41.693
for going five over.

22:41.694 --> 22:44.663
This isn't just Wesley
Enterprises playing it safe.

22:44.664 --> 22:45.864
We've seen literally everything

22:45.865 --> 22:46.965
from this company.

22:46.966 --> 22:48.199
Solar powered blankets,

22:48.200 --> 22:50.135
mission heat tiles,
robot sex toys.

22:50.136 --> 22:51.403
I think it's safe...

22:51.404 --> 22:53.572
To expect the unexpected.

22:53.573 --> 22:56.675
Is Paul Wesley sparking
another scientific revolution?

22:56.676 --> 22:58.410
We'll just have to wait and see.

23:02.582 --> 23:03.516
And we say they fear

23:03.517 --> 23:05.350
what they do not understand.

23:05.351 --> 23:08.554
Talk about some of the good
that Wesley Enterprises...

23:25.905 --> 23:27.205
It is with our faith in you

23:27.206 --> 23:30.976
that we commit her
body, heart, her being,

23:30.977 --> 23:32.678
into your hands.

23:32.679 --> 23:34.013
Into your hands.

23:35.247 --> 23:36.649
Hello.

23:47.093 --> 23:48.527
Hey, hey, hey, hey!

23:48.528 --> 23:49.462
Step away from each other.

23:49.462 --> 23:50.196
Hey, that's enough.

23:50.196 --> 23:51.030
Back off.

23:51.031 --> 23:52.263
Hey, hey, hey, hey.

23:52.264 --> 23:52.932
You back up and stay there.

23:52.933 --> 23:54.032
Don't move.

23:54.033 --> 23:56.101
- You back off, asshole.
- Do not move.

23:56.102 --> 23:57.769
Oh my God!

23:57.770 --> 24:01.873
Hey, what the fuck
is the matter with you?

24:03.510 --> 24:04.510
Hey!

24:05.311 --> 24:06.546
Get in the car.

24:08.280 --> 24:10.449
I wrote a poem.

24:27.066 --> 24:28.567
What about the soul?

24:28.568 --> 24:32.003
What about the fact that we
are created in God's own image?

24:32.004 --> 24:34.272
Quite frankly, I'm shocked
that a Nobel Prize winner

24:34.273 --> 24:36.107
like Dr. Beckett
would engage in work

24:36.108 --> 24:38.309
that seems to suggest that
being human is nothing special.

24:38.310 --> 24:39.578
Which on the face of it...

24:39.579 --> 24:41.580
Actually, Senator,
I think human beings

24:41.581 --> 24:45.250
are extremely special
and worth saving.

24:45.251 --> 24:48.286
Senator, if someone has
early stage Alzheimer's,

24:48.287 --> 24:50.255
then if the technology
that she advocates

24:50.256 --> 24:52.958
becomes reality, it
could save them, correct?

24:52.959 --> 24:56.227
I believe there's a reason
why we don't live forever.

24:56.228 --> 24:57.462
We're not meant to.

24:57.463 --> 24:59.030
Human beings weren't
meant to fly either.

24:59.031 --> 25:00.699
We weren't meant
to travel in space.

25:00.700 --> 25:02.734
We weren't meant to
talk to each other

25:02.735 --> 25:04.135
from across the world.

25:04.136 --> 25:05.370
- Doctor...
- Dialysis,

25:05.371 --> 25:08.206
heart transplants,
bypass surgery.

25:08.207 --> 25:11.543
You're familiar with that
one, aren't ya, Senator?

25:11.544 --> 25:13.745
Well, since I see you
wish to make this personal,

25:13.746 --> 25:15.146
I'd just throw that
question right back at you.

25:15.147 --> 25:16.582
That's a good
point, Dr. Beckett.

25:16.583 --> 25:19.250
Many are familiar with the
tragedy that took your daughter.

25:19.251 --> 25:21.186
Are you saying in
theory you'd really

25:21.187 --> 25:23.454
be willing to
replace her this way?

25:23.455 --> 25:25.090
Don't you think as
her mother that might

25:25.091 --> 25:26.592
cheapen her memory?

25:26.593 --> 25:29.661
If you see what we're doing
as Frankensteining someone.

25:29.662 --> 25:31.096
Which is absolutely

25:31.097 --> 25:32.130
- not the case.
- That is exactly

25:32.131 --> 25:33.364
what you're doing.

25:33.365 --> 25:35.200
We are talking
about transplants.

25:35.201 --> 25:37.869
The idea behind the technology
that God has given us?

25:37.870 --> 25:39.170
That's not the problem.

25:39.171 --> 25:42.073
But with what some
people might do with it.

25:42.074 --> 25:43.274
This theory

25:43.275 --> 25:44.076
- that Dr. Beckett...
- This is not

25:44.077 --> 25:45.443
a theory, Senator.

25:45.444 --> 25:47.378
This will happen.

25:47.379 --> 25:51.116
You will see us save someone's
life with this technology.

25:51.117 --> 25:54.152
And you will know that we did it

25:54.153 --> 25:55.588
and not your God.

25:57.456 --> 25:59.224
That did not help us.

25:59.225 --> 26:00.926
These people don't
care about science, Paul.

26:00.927 --> 26:02.427
We're trying to lay
the groundwork here

26:02.428 --> 26:03.629
to gain some credibility.

26:03.630 --> 26:05.230
You can't go off book like that.

26:05.231 --> 26:08.133
Since when did credibility
involve arguing with the right?

26:08.134 --> 26:10.101
That's the conversation
you shouldn't be having.

26:10.102 --> 26:13.104
It validates their opinions.

26:13.105 --> 26:14.405
Dr. Beckett, you need

26:14.406 --> 26:15.641
to come downstairs immediately.

26:15.642 --> 26:16.642
Why?

26:17.944 --> 26:20.946
Her patterns spike when
we speak directly to her.

26:20.947 --> 26:21.947
Watch.

26:23.215 --> 26:27.219
She knows that I'm speaking
specifically to her.

26:29.689 --> 26:33.825
Amelia.

26:33.826 --> 26:35.126
Ellen.

26:35.127 --> 26:36.695
Paul.

26:36.696 --> 26:37.696
Max.

26:38.798 --> 26:42.234
Amelia.

26:45.304 --> 26:47.505
Okay, let me try something.

26:47.506 --> 26:49.207
Hundreds of years of
research and discovery

26:49.208 --> 26:51.542
and the fix might be as
simple as a light bulb.

26:51.543 --> 26:53.078
What are you talking about?

26:53.079 --> 26:54.112
Voltage.

26:54.113 --> 26:55.781
Activity increase.

26:55.782 --> 26:57.849
Consciousness to level six.

27:10.362 --> 27:12.931
Beginning voltage
increase in 10,

27:12.932 --> 27:14.165
nine,

27:14.166 --> 27:15.233
eight,

27:15.234 --> 27:16.467
seven,

27:16.468 --> 27:17.635
six,

27:17.636 --> 27:18.670
five,

27:18.671 --> 27:19.671
four,

27:19.672 --> 27:20.872
three,

27:20.873 --> 27:22.007
two,

27:22.008 --> 27:23.008
one.

27:24.276 --> 27:25.778
Subject is online.

27:39.658 --> 27:40.658
Amelia,

27:42.962 --> 27:44.296
can you hear me?

27:50.870 --> 27:53.039
Do you know where you are?

28:00.579 --> 28:02.548
Do you know who you are?

28:11.457 --> 28:14.025
Can you tell me your name?

28:25.371 --> 28:27.305
I'm Amelia Summerland.

28:37.850 --> 28:41.087
I know, I know, I know, I know.

28:41.988 --> 28:42.889
Wait, wait.

28:42.890 --> 28:44.823
Quiet, quiet everybody.

28:44.824 --> 28:46.091
Oh shit.

28:46.092 --> 28:46.926
Heart stop.

28:46.927 --> 28:48.093
Heart stop!

28:48.094 --> 28:49.427
- Stop it.
- Get a hold of her.

28:52.731 --> 28:53.565
You're safe.

28:53.566 --> 28:54.665
You're safe, Amelia.

28:54.666 --> 28:56.034
You're safe.

28:56.035 --> 28:57.368
You're safe.

29:04.743 --> 29:08.013
We've lost everything.

29:08.014 --> 29:10.381
We need to tell her.

29:10.382 --> 29:11.649
She won't be able to handle it.

29:11.650 --> 29:12.750
It couldn't possibly be worse

29:12.751 --> 29:15.353
than the episode we just had.

29:15.354 --> 29:17.655
Blunt her emotions.

29:17.656 --> 29:19.325
It'll keep her calm.

29:30.369 --> 29:33.471
So, um, what that means, Amelia,

29:33.472 --> 29:36.341
is that you will never age.

29:36.342 --> 29:38.243
You'll never get sick.

29:38.244 --> 29:40.278
You'll never die.

29:40.279 --> 29:42.949
You're still you, Amelia, but...

29:44.250 --> 29:46.517
You're different now.

29:46.518 --> 29:49.755
Tell me what you're
thinking, Amelia.

29:52.391 --> 29:54.160
Who are all of you?

29:59.165 --> 30:01.867
Wesley Enterprises
experienced a record low

30:01.868 --> 30:03.801
last quarter but
remain optimistic.

30:03.802 --> 30:05.203
Insiders suggest something big...

30:05.204 --> 30:06.304
I want to announce it.

30:06.305 --> 30:07.505
She's not ready.

30:07.506 --> 30:08.773
She's talking,
for the love of God.

30:08.774 --> 30:10.608
She struggles
with motor control.

30:10.609 --> 30:12.177
She can't walk
without assistance.

30:12.178 --> 30:13.979
Her nervous system
is a disaster.

30:13.980 --> 30:15.746
The interface, it overclocks.

30:15.747 --> 30:16.948
The computer can't keep up.

30:16.949 --> 30:19.217
She's had several
catastrophic failures.

30:19.218 --> 30:23.389
When the computer resets,
we have to completely rebuild.

30:25.824 --> 30:28.626
We're six days from an
update with the board.

30:28.627 --> 30:30.328
We have to make something up.

30:30.329 --> 30:32.063
How long does it
take to rebuild?

30:32.064 --> 30:33.431
Weeks.

30:33.432 --> 30:34.400
I mean, it's not a simple.
23 hours to be

30:34.401 --> 30:35.634
- precise.
- Process.

30:36.535 --> 30:37.802
Here's what we're gonna do.

30:37.803 --> 30:38.770
We're gonna put
her back on line.

30:38.771 --> 30:40.005
I'm letting Carter meet her.

30:40.006 --> 30:41.472
It's too soon.

30:41.473 --> 30:43.975
We have to have something
to show these people.

30:43.976 --> 30:45.410
Imagine how they're gonna react

30:45.411 --> 30:46.978
when they see Carter
reunited with his dead wife.

30:46.979 --> 30:48.980
The emotional stimuli
might cause another failure.

30:48.981 --> 30:49.916
We have to do something.

30:49.917 --> 30:51.116
What about Carter?

30:51.117 --> 30:52.583
I'm worried what
that might do to him.

30:52.584 --> 30:56.588
I'm worried about keeping
this project funded.

31:18.810 --> 31:20.146
Carter.

31:21.180 --> 31:22.180
Amelia.

31:27.019 --> 31:28.620
You have a visitor.

31:59.751 --> 32:01.819
Hello.

32:01.820 --> 32:03.889
We'll be right outside.

32:42.494 --> 32:46.031
Do you know what
they did with my ring?

32:46.032 --> 32:47.033
Your ring?

32:48.167 --> 32:51.070
It's been missing
since I woke up.

33:07.019 --> 33:10.421
They wouldn't let me see you.

33:10.422 --> 33:11.422
Why not?

33:16.928 --> 33:19.130
They said there's
things they don't want us

33:19.131 --> 33:20.632
to talk about yet.

33:23.302 --> 33:28.173
They said it's the only
way that you'll get better.

33:28.174 --> 33:29.175
Am I sick?

33:33.679 --> 33:35.513
Not anymore.

33:35.514 --> 33:38.417
Then why do I
need to get better?

33:39.285 --> 33:40.918
Millie.

33:41.987 --> 33:44.490
There's something in my ear.

33:45.524 --> 33:47.425
I can feel it there.

33:47.426 --> 33:48.893
I'll talk to the doctors.

33:48.894 --> 33:49.894
My ring.

33:50.762 --> 33:53.365
Can I have it back now, please?

33:55.501 --> 33:56.502
Of course.

34:17.255 --> 34:19.425
I never stopped believing.

34:21.827 --> 34:23.562
I don't understand.

34:24.630 --> 34:25.630
Who are you?

34:27.799 --> 34:28.734
I can feel my hand stall now.

34:28.734 --> 34:29.734
Really?

34:33.405 --> 34:34.405
What?

34:35.440 --> 34:36.907
Somebody get in here!

34:36.908 --> 34:37.708
Get back.

34:37.710 --> 34:38.976
Move!

34:38.976 --> 34:39.976
Tell me what's happening.

34:40.713 --> 34:42.179
Get her legs.

34:42.181 --> 34:43.514
Don't worry, Carter,
this has happened before.

34:43.514 --> 34:44.815
Get her to the chair.

34:44.815 --> 34:46.083
One, two, up.

34:46.083 --> 34:47.717
Tell me what's happening!

34:47.719 --> 34:50.420
Mr. Summerland,
you need to leave.

34:50.422 --> 34:52.223
Mr. Summerland, you
need to leave now.

34:52.224 --> 34:54.559
What are you doing to my wife?

34:57.429 --> 34:59.029
What are you doing to my wife?

34:59.030 --> 35:00.298
Get control of her, Max.

35:00.299 --> 35:02.733
I'm workin' on it!

35:53.419 --> 35:54.619
Don't look.

35:54.620 --> 35:56.254
We noticed when Ellen
would play Mozart

35:56.255 --> 35:59.390
over the intercom your
brain activity would spike.

35:59.391 --> 36:03.594
So, we figured this
might help you redevelop

36:03.595 --> 36:06.030
some of those
broken connections.

36:06.031 --> 36:08.033
And this little present.

36:10.001 --> 36:13.771
This is a textbook example
of art meeting science.

36:13.772 --> 36:16.574
When Dr. Beckett
developed microbes

36:16.575 --> 36:20.445
that specifically target
cells to help them grow,

36:20.446 --> 36:23.080
this was the first
clinical subject.

36:23.081 --> 36:26.418
This plant hasn't
aged in over a decade.

36:29.821 --> 36:30.822
So it's...

36:32.358 --> 36:33.758
Real?

36:33.759 --> 36:35.460
Absolutely.

36:35.461 --> 36:38.297
But just, you know,
not all of it.

36:39.898 --> 36:41.733
I guess it's like you.

36:43.034 --> 36:44.034
Like me.

36:45.136 --> 36:46.572
You are Amelia.

36:52.744 --> 36:55.112
I don't remember if I played.

36:55.113 --> 36:56.213
Oh, don't worry.

36:56.214 --> 36:57.315
It's easy, here.

36:57.316 --> 36:58.349
We're just gonna do the basics.

36:58.350 --> 36:59.550
I'll show you.

36:59.551 --> 37:00.551
Come look.

37:01.687 --> 37:02.687
This is C.

37:05.223 --> 37:06.725
Go ahead, play it.

37:10.061 --> 37:12.129
What are you feeling?

37:12.130 --> 37:13.130
Nothing.

37:15.967 --> 37:16.967
Okay.

37:17.903 --> 37:19.337
I'm gonna try
something different.

37:19.338 --> 37:21.238
You're gonna feel something
completely different,

37:21.239 --> 37:25.076
but it's a good feeling,
so don't worry, okay?

37:28.079 --> 37:30.515
Emotions
processing unit reacting.

37:30.516 --> 37:32.851
Okay, play it again.

37:44.596 --> 37:45.596
That...

37:47.533 --> 37:48.700
is beautiful.

37:51.937 --> 37:53.871
Okay, play it again.

37:53.872 --> 37:56.006
But take it easy, okay?

37:56.007 --> 37:58.577
Your mind's trying to catch up.

38:09.755 --> 38:10.822
That's music.

38:27.072 --> 38:30.240
It wasn't my decision to
introduce her to you yet.

38:30.241 --> 38:32.309
She wasn't ready.

38:32.310 --> 38:35.146
We found the problem
and fixed it.

38:41.152 --> 38:43.488
Why isn't she moving?

38:43.489 --> 38:45.956
She's in standby mode.

38:45.957 --> 38:47.958
Unaware of anything around
her until we give her

38:47.959 --> 38:51.028
the verbal command
to wake up again.

38:51.029 --> 38:52.598
It's like sleeping.

38:53.599 --> 38:54.865
- No.
- Carter.

38:54.866 --> 38:56.300
You have her on
a remote control?

38:56.301 --> 38:57.535
It's not like that.

38:57.536 --> 38:58.370
This isn't right.

38:58.370 --> 38:59.304
She was at peace.

38:59.305 --> 39:00.671
Carter, please, please.

39:00.672 --> 39:01.507
I understand.

39:01.508 --> 39:02.873
I really do.

39:02.874 --> 39:06.478
It looks very strange
seeing her like this.

39:10.048 --> 39:13.150
Where is your
daughter now, Ellen?

39:13.151 --> 39:15.520
I beg your pardon?

39:15.521 --> 39:17.488
Where is her body?

39:17.489 --> 39:18.723
Carter.

39:18.724 --> 39:20.090
Where is she.

39:20.091 --> 39:21.427
In the ground.

39:24.362 --> 39:25.864
Where is Amelia?

39:34.473 --> 39:37.408
Find a different test subject.

39:37.409 --> 39:39.745
You know we can't do that.

39:47.285 --> 39:49.186
Wesley Enterprises,
the tech giant

39:49.187 --> 39:50.788
positioned in Cedar
Rapids, Iowa...

39:50.789 --> 39:52.857
Shocked the world today
when founder Paul Wesley

39:52.858 --> 39:55.493
announced what he says is
the first successful copy

39:55.494 --> 39:56.994
of a human brain.

39:56.995 --> 39:59.430
This will give new hope
to Alzheimer's patients,

39:59.431 --> 40:02.366
to parapalegics, to those
suffering from terminal illness.

40:02.367 --> 40:03.268
Our Amelia

40:03.269 --> 40:04.502
is the future.

40:04.503 --> 40:06.671
Wesley released
no images of Amelia,

40:06.672 --> 40:09.173
but promised to unveil her
publicly three months from now.

40:09.174 --> 40:10.675
Wesley's announcement
sent shock waves

40:10.676 --> 40:13.143
through both the medical
and religious communities.

40:13.144 --> 40:14.645
Protestors rallied
outside the capital

40:14.646 --> 40:16.280
calling for strict legislation...

40:16.281 --> 40:19.550
That clearly defined the
definition of human and machine.

40:19.551 --> 40:22.286
Proponents of the new technology
suggest current definitions

40:22.287 --> 40:25.422
are vague and open
to interpretation.

40:25.423 --> 40:27.625
My colleagues, it would
be foolish to suggest

40:27.626 --> 40:31.095
that the world would be
better off without technology.

40:31.096 --> 40:34.899
Without our advanced care
for the sick and elderly.

40:34.900 --> 40:38.402
But these technologies
work in harmony

40:38.403 --> 40:41.706
with the human spirit,
not against it.

40:41.707 --> 40:43.974
These are gifts from God

40:43.975 --> 40:47.912
and if we attempt to
escape from these gifts,

40:47.913 --> 40:51.482
to reach higher than we
were intended to reach,

40:51.483 --> 40:55.086
we will have become
arrogant and foolhardy.

40:57.856 --> 40:59.924
Hi, Carter, this
is Senator Williams office.

40:59.925 --> 41:01.191
We received your message.

41:01.192 --> 41:03.460
We'd like to speak with
you as soon as possible.

41:27.619 --> 41:29.019
More of her memories are turning

41:29.020 --> 41:31.656
but four weeks to
play Twinkle Twinkle?

41:31.657 --> 41:32.890
I am sorry, Max.

41:32.891 --> 41:34.491
Oh no, no, no,
it's not your fault.

41:34.492 --> 41:36.226
Don't apologize.

41:36.227 --> 41:39.296
The important thing is that
you're making progress.

41:39.297 --> 41:40.330
And that is good?

41:40.331 --> 41:43.033
It's very good, Amelia,

41:43.034 --> 41:45.836
considering most of what you
remember was left in fragments.

41:45.837 --> 41:50.741
We have the data here showing
you're making huge strides.

41:50.742 --> 41:52.977
Yesterday you told us a story,

41:52.978 --> 41:54.879
the one in the park.

41:54.880 --> 41:56.214
Do you remember?

41:57.515 --> 41:58.515
Yes.

42:07.458 --> 42:08.826
I'm by a lake.

42:08.827 --> 42:10.294
I jump in.

42:10.295 --> 42:14.065
This other man does, too, but
I can't remember his face.

42:18.904 --> 42:21.907
Some kids nearby
are laughing at us.

42:27.312 --> 42:29.147
My face is underwater.

42:34.653 --> 42:36.154
I can feel summer.

42:37.422 --> 42:39.590
Now we're sitting under a tree.

42:39.591 --> 42:40.891
I'm reading a poem to the man,

42:40.892 --> 42:43.161
something I wrote, I think.

42:50.135 --> 42:52.870
I can't remember his face.

42:52.871 --> 42:54.905
We're walking through a garden.

42:54.906 --> 42:57.174
There's a dance by.

42:57.175 --> 42:59.110
I don't understand why.

43:00.679 --> 43:03.648
There's a feeling of happiness.

43:07.052 --> 43:08.987
A girl walks in, she...

43:11.256 --> 43:13.123
I want you to keep
thinking about that, Amelia,

43:13.124 --> 43:14.892
that exact moment.

43:14.893 --> 43:18.428
Everything is blurring
together, Dr. Beckett.

43:18.429 --> 43:19.496
Where is the ring?

43:21.332 --> 43:23.067
The screeching...

43:23.068 --> 43:24.068
sound.

43:32.678 --> 43:36.814
Warning.

43:41.152 --> 43:42.821
All systems offline.

43:44.322 --> 43:46.657
Well, it's very strange.

43:46.658 --> 43:48.759
It's too unpredictable.

43:48.760 --> 43:50.828
There's nothing about
what she remembers

43:50.829 --> 43:52.997
that makes any sense.

43:52.998 --> 43:55.000
She needs information.

43:57.268 --> 43:58.435
She doesn't know what to do

43:58.436 --> 44:01.072
with the information
she has now.

44:02.540 --> 44:04.574
Just keep her playing scales.

44:04.575 --> 44:06.010
Understood?

44:06.011 --> 44:07.078
Understood.

44:18.990 --> 44:20.424
Build.

